  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving Water and Sanitation Infrastructure in Northern Haiti</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Haiti has the lowest rates of access to improved water and sanitation infrastructure in the western hemisphere. The water and sanitation situation in Haiti is among the most dire in the Western Hemisphere. According to the World Health Organization/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Program, 85% of urban residents and 51% of rural residents have access to improved water services. Access to an improved sanitation facility is extremely low in both urban (24%) and rural (10%) areas of the country. 

Haiti Outreach is already present in the Northeast department of Haiti implementing a project to drill and rehabilitate a total of 100 community wells, along with community well management training for long-term sustainability, sanitation education and the promotion of household latrines. The partnership with American Red Cross will leverage Haiti Outreach&apos;s experience of providing a &#x201C;one-stop shop&#x201D; for water and sanitation interventions &#x2013; an approach that combines community mobilization/social engineering and technical drilling. This partnership with the Red Cross will focus on six communal areas in the North and Northeast Departments of Haiti.  

The project will conduct community surveys, train water management committees, conduct sanitation and hygiene education and latrine promotion, train 2 sanitation teachers per community, drill wells and build the well houses, and conduct monthly inspections for 2 years.</narrative>
  </description>
